

"Entropy measures how unpredictable a password is."

-- How many guesses would an attacker need, on average, to crack this password?

Entropy uses a formula:
    Entropy = log2(N^L)
    N = size of character set , L = password length
    
    Using log rules: - When coding:
        Entropy = L x log2(N)

To calculate entropy:
S1: Work out the character set size(N)
Typical:
    - Lowercase letters -> 26
    - Uppercase letters -> 26
    - digits -> 10
    - symbols -> ~32(depends on leniency)

Therefore:
    - If a password uses:
        Lowercase + uppercase + digits
    Then:
        N = 26 + 26 + 10 = 62

Calculate Entropy value using this value(N)

Example: Password  :: P@ssw0rd!
Length = 9,  Char set: uppercase, Lowercase, digit, symbol   ->  N = ~94 assuming symbols

Entropy = 9 x log2(94) =~ 58.99 bits 
Measured in bits: Represents one binary decision - 
    How many binary decisions(Y/N) must an attacker take to guess a password.

log2(x) - "What power do I raise 2 to, to get X?" - inverse of powers of 2
    log2(8) = 3

Interpreting entropy:

| Entropy (bits) | Strength    |
| -------------- | ----------- |
| < 28           | Very weak   |
| 28 - 35          | Weak        |
| 36 - 59          | Reasonable  |
| 60 - 127         | Strong      |
| 128+           | Very strong |

However ! Entropy assumes: random character selection, no reuse of patterns.

Entropy then overestimates password security when users choose predictable patters.
    Such as substitutions like @ for.

Therefore, to make this value more inclusive:
reduce entropy value if repeated characters and penalise dict words -- 
